==English==

===Phrase===
'''[[stick]]s [[and]] [[stone]]s'''

# Evocative of the saying ''"sticks and stones may'' (or ''will'') ''break my bones, but words'' (or ''names'') ''will never hurt'' (or ''harm'') ''me"''.
#*'''1957,''' Brendan Gill, ''The Day the Money Stopped''
#*:‘You cheap dead-beat son of a bitch.’ ‘'''Sticks and stones'''.’
#*'''1993,''' ''[[w:The Independent|The Independent]]'', 15 May
#*:He has come through the worst and now presents a stoical ‘'''sticks and stones'''’ front to his detractors.
#*'''2003,''' ''[[w:Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl|Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl]]'' (film)
#*:Elizabeth Swann: You're despicable!
#*:Jack Sparrow: '''Sticks and stones''', love.

